      "text": "Social bonds are affected by spatial configurations— the arrangement of seating, where the administrative offices are placed, location of coffee shops.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "ce9227ff5edf65fd",
      "text": "Enzymes combine or cleve molecules through the attraction, placement, orientation, thus changing rate of interaction—meta control is through the of amount of enzyme or configuration of enzymes. Pathology in any of these aspects unbalances the situation producing too much or too little of an essential component to the life of the organism.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "3bb6427802a0119d",
      "text": "Almost all metabolic processes in the cell need enzymes in order to occur at rates fast enough to sustain life. (Wikipedia accessed Oct 27, 2017).\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "72fd483ec9dda864",
      "text": "So here is my big point. Institutions are moving faster than neighborhoods and they take advantage of this speed (often called efficiency), often taking over functions that would be better performed by neighbors in neighborhoods. My belief is that institutions have a certain social and physical configuration which allows them to be catalytic. They can be thought of as sociopolitical enzymes. My intention is to produce faster and better enzyme-like configurations that work in voluntary situations, specifically neighborhoods, and out perform less adaptable settings, specifically top down hierarchical institutions.\n\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "c819f3ddc38f3803",
      "text": "# BEGINNING\nSocieties are beginning to become overwhelmingly complex, but we don't know how to think about it yet. We don’t yet know how to participate in massive complexity. Some of us turn a blind eye to it and are swept along. Others, comfortable with a slower simpler time, try to withdraw, or even attempt to stop it or slow it down.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "09e4d11bd175db72",
      "text": "Incalculable complexity is surfacing increasingly at the social level. For example: culturally, we have moved from English freemen and serfs doing the farming with hand tools, to industrialized mechanization, then to complete industrialization of farming, now to global agribusiness. As the world becomes more and more interconnected we experience the consequences. There is an explosion of combinations of interactions driving the complexity we are experiencing. The numbers, the density, and the rapidity of communication between people, across cultures and continents begin to create patterns similar to those we have discovered in physics, chemistry, and biology. One hundred years ago we understood such overwhelming complexity only in of physics, chemistry and microbiology.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "dd55bbbf46d99263",
      "text": "In physics, chemistry and biology, we can appreciate role of time and movement and speed. The small- er things are, the faster they tend to move. At the atomic and molecular level things move very fast and unpredictably. At the subatomic levels of physics there are lots of things moving even faster. At all these levels things are running into one another, changing, transforming, combining, breaking. The re- sulting macroscopic behaviors, the behaviors of large chunks, show up as kinds of averages, obscuring the mechanisms and the unimaginable variation be- low the surface of those visible chunks.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "d47318730a99ff0c",
      "text": "# MASTERING COMPLEXITY\nSomething interesting happens between the scales of chemistry and biochemistry—that is between chemistry and biology. This something may hold a key to the mastery of social complexity.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "0ae873df52ffbe32",
      "text": "It is easy to unreflectively assume that everything in the universe is happening at the speed of our own ex- periences, at the speed of human thought and con- versation and bodily motion. Such a default assump- tion occurs because we tend to image things by anal- ogy with our embodied experiences. \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
